😄 That’s one of those jokes that’s funny because it plays with two different meanings of “right.”

* “Two wrongs don’t make a right” is the proverb: retaliating against wrongdoing doesn’t make it morally correct.
* ”…but three lefts do” switches from moral “right” to directional “right.”

If you imagine making three 90° left turns:

* Start facing North.
* Left → West.
* Left → South.
* Left → East.

After three lefts, you’re facing the same direction as if you’d made one right turn.

It’s a clever little example of semantic ambiguity—a sentence that pivots on a word with two meanings. One moment “right” means morally correct; the next it means the direction opposite left.

It’s the kind of wordplay that rewards noticing the hidden change in context.